article.description:
Dawn Staley scored 20 points as the
Charlotte Sting beat the Indiana Fever 80-50 Wednesday night for
the second-most lopsided victory in team history.
article.headline: Sting lead Rockers by one game
article.linkText: Sting crush Fever thanks to second-half outburst
article.story:
CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Dawn Staley scored 20 points as the
Charlotte Sting beat the Indiana Fever 80-50 Wednesday night for
the second-most lopsided victory in team history.

Charlotte beat Washington by 36 points in 1998.

Tamika Catchings scored 19 points and Natalie Williams added 13
points and eight rebounds for the Fever (14-17), who blew a
13-point first-half lead to lose for the seventh time in eight
games.

The Sting snapped a two-game losing streak and opened a one-game
lead over Cleveland in the battle for second place in the Eastern
Conference and home-court advantage in the first round of the
playoffs.

Andrea Stinson and Allison Feaster each added 16 points for the
Sting (17-14), who closed the game by outscoring the Fever 48-16.

Indiana, which shot 35 percent, trails New York and Connecticut
by one game in the race for the final playoff spot in the East with
three games left.

The game was tied 34-34 when Catchings, Indiana's leading scorer
and rebounder, picked up her fifth personal foul. With Catchings on
the bench, the Sting immediately went on a 14-2 run, capped off by
Staley's back-to-back 3-pointers, to take a 48-36 lead with 12:30
left.

Indiana raced out to a 5-0 lead as Charlotte missed its first
five shots. Stephanie White's two free throws with 8:30 left put
the Fever ahead 24-11.

But Stinson's 3-pointer and 3-point-play on consecutive
possessions started a 15-2 Charlotte run that tied the game at 26
with 2:18 remaining. The Fever led 31-30 at halftime despite nine
turnovers. They finished with 20 turnovers.
